Qo-Sev was a Kowloon clerk-tradition theorist who wrote during the post-Ashfall emergency governance period.
His central treatise argued that legitimate authority during disaster is defined by procedural continuity, not by outcomes.
Qo-Sev formulated the "provision sequence": assess need, assign authority, record action, then shelter — in that order.
Breaking the sequence, he argued, produced governance that survived the crisis but lost legitimacy in the aftermath.
His work emerged from the Neon Covenant's experience administering rations when record systems were partially destroyed.
Qo-Sev observed that crisis administrators who skipped attestation steps during emergencies faced accountability crises later.
The treatise was not well received by Kowloon's field commanders, who found its procedural demands impractical under fire.
It gained influence after the Ashfall's immediate crisis passed, when the Jade Magistracy faced questions about undocumented emergency requisitions.
Later clerk-tradition scholars treated Qo-Sev as the theoretical foundation for emergency legitimacy doctrine in the five-city corridor.
His name appears in Midgaard's Lantern Registry as a "consulted external source" on civic emergency charter drafting.
The treatise exists in partial copies; no complete original is confirmed to survive.

